title: Ramen Vegetable Soup
summary: Ramen Vegetable Soup is a dairy free soup. This recipe makes 6 servings with 199 calories, 5g of protein, and 7g of fat each. For $1.01 per serving, this recipe covers 14% of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. This recipe is typical of Japanese cuisine. 7143 people have made this recipe and would make it again. A mixture of canned tomatoes, juice of lime, onion, and a handful of other ingredients are all it takes to make this recipe so delicious. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes around 45 minutes. Autumn will be even more special with this recipe. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 86%. This score is awesome. Similar recipes include Ramen Noodle Vegetable Soup, Vegetable Ramen Stir Fry, and Vegetable Ramen Stir Fry.

winePairing.pairingText: Riesling, Sake, and Sauvignon Blanc are my top picks for Ramen Noodles. Saké is an obvious choice when it comes to Japanese food. If you want to stick to grape wine, though, you might opt for sauvignon blanc or riesling. The Dr. Thanisch Graacher Himmelreich Spatlese Riesling with a 4.5 out of 5 star rating seems like a good match. It costs about 19 dollars per bottle.

productMatches.title: Dr. Thanisch Graacher Himmelreich Spatlese Riesling
productMatches.description: Graach is an excellent wine growing village in the heart of the Middle Mosel. The steep slopes of the Graacher Himmelreich vineyard are facing South-West. They are exclusively planted with Riesling.The nose displays a sweet floral quality of plummeria, fresh peach with a touch of petrol character which is common in German wines. Often the more age a German wine has, the stronger the petrol character. There is nothing wrong with wines with this aroma. This 2003 vintage, only shows a slight – medium petrol aroma. Brimful with character, the Himmelreich Spätlese palate is a wonderful mix of peach, honey and mango. The medium weight interplays enticingly with the finely bound acidity.

instructions: In a large pot, heat olive oil over medium. Add onion, carrots, celery and zucchini; sauté until soft, about 6 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Add tomatoes, broth, water and lime juice; bring to a boil. Add ramen, reduce heat and simmer until noodles are tender, 3 minutes. Season with salt, pepper and Sriracha sauce if desired. Serve immediately and top bowls with cilantro and chopped green onions.If serving next-day or as leftovers, store soup in pot in refrigerator, place over medium heat and add enough water to cover vegetables. Bring to a boil then reduce heat and simmer until warmed through.Enjoy!
